1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:12,960
 Thank you so much, Boris, for this elogy. And the day when I die, I think I'll call on you to make sure that you are around.

2
00:00:12,960 --> 00:00:23,000
 So thank you so much for bringing us together. Thank you for carrying the flag year after year and celebrating the 30th anniversary.

3
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:32,000
 Philippe was telling me that it gets better every year, so I don't know what else you will invent for next year after this fantastic conference.

4
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:40,000
 But also the tremendous singers that we enjoyed all so much. So thank you very, very much.

5
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:45,000
 For those of you who are not interested in my speech, I encourage you to look at the beauty of the scene.

6
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:52,000
 Because that's also the reason why we all come here. Dubrovnik is not just you, Boris, and all your team.

7
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:58,000
 But it's also the beauty of the setting that you have selected and the beauty of your country.

8
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:08,000
 So in your honour, Boris, I'm going to quote a very famous poet from Croatia, Ivan Gundulic.

9
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:13,000
 And just for you and your Croatian team members:

10
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:22,000
 O Licepa, O Draga, O Slavka, Svoboda.

11
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:26,000
 Okay, for the non-Croatian around the table:

12
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:30,000
 O beautiful, O dear, O sweet freedom.

13
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:41,000
 And I think in the context of what we are leaving at the moment, particularly in this corner of the world, in Europe, to celebrate freedom in the way he did, is something that is...

14
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:53,000
 Very important. And I would like to, on this occasion, salute our Ukrainian friend and celebrate with courage.

15
00:01:53,000 --> 00:02:09,000
 Yes, I know, that's for him that I said that. Thank you. Yeah.

16
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:11,000
 And I also agree about that.

17
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:14,000
 And it's for you as well. Second round of applause for you.

18
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:26,000
 So your programme, Boris, offers a snapshot of policy making in a world of transition.

19
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:36,000
 And this world of transition is increasingly a world of profound uncertainty for us economic policy makers.

20
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:48,000
 If you look back at speeches of former central bankers, and I'm sure some of you really enjoy that exercise occasionally,

21
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:58,000
 policy makers in every era probably claim that the world has never been more uncertain.

22
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:06,000
 Indeed, that might well be true. And the world is not necessarily more tumultuous than in the past.

23
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:10,000
 But the nature of the risks that we are facing is unusual.

24
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:22,000
 Increasingly, volatility in growth and inflation will not only be driven by the business cycle, which we understand relatively well,

25
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:32,000
 at least some of you do. Or even by the financial cycle, which we understand a little less well,

26
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:36,000
 but can at least try to anticipate and preempt.

27
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:50,000
 It will also be driven by a pair of major structural forces that we have next to no experience.

28
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:56,000
 Number one, geopolitical fragmentation. Number two, climate change.

29
00:03:56,000 --> 00:04:02,000
 And I hope you don't mind if I step into the territory of those who study those two risks,

30
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:09,000
 to try to explain to you how very special they are and how, as policy makers, we can address them.

31
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:17,000
 The fragmenting of a previously highly globalised world is a type of risk that advanced economies have not faced

32
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:29,000
 since the period after the first world war. And a rapidly, ever so rapidly changing climate is a risk that we have not seen for millennia.

33
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:39,000
 So in my view, these two, this pair of risks, presents three very, very specific factors for us policy makers.

34
00:04:39,000 --> 00:04:51,000
 First, they are particularly difficult to quantify and forecast. We saw this in Europe after the Russian horrible invasion of Ukraine.

35
00:04:51,000 --> 00:05:00,000
 But more generally, political risks create various types of spillovers that are just hard to map ex ante.

36
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:05,000
 That said, there are certain studies that try to quantify the impact of conflict.

37
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:17,000
 I'll mention one, which, for example, estimates that for countries that are geographically close to a war zone, output falls by more than 10% over five years,

38
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:22,000
 and inflation rises by five percentage points on average.

39
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:36,000
 Another study finds that firms with greater exposure to geopolitical risk experience an increased probability of default, lower market valuations, and higher financing costs.

40
00:05:36,000 --> 00:05:49,000
 So, climate change is similarly hard to forecast, as is visible, for example, in the struggle the insurance industry is facing to accurately price climate risk,

41
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:55,000
 to the point where many of them are simply saying, "Sorry, but no, we don't insure anymore."

42
00:05:55,000 --> 00:05:57,000
 As simple as that.

43
00:05:57,000 --> 00:06:07,000
 An increasing frequency of extreme weather events means that claim costs no longer correspond to the historical data used to price risk.

44
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:15,000
 Last year set a record for the highest number of insured natural catastrophes yet.

45
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:20,000
 And climate change increases uncertainty about inflation.

46
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:26,000
 ECB research finds that, thank you, Luke Levin is here tonight, isn't he?

47
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:28,000
 Hi, thank you for doing that.

48
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:43,000
 So, ECB research finds that extreme summer heat could ultimately push up food inflation in the Euro area by between one and two percentage point.

49
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:47,000
 So, that's the first factor.

50
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:52,000
 The second factor that makes these risks special is that they reinforce each other.

51
00:06:52,000 --> 00:06:58,000
 A weakening multilateral order not only makes it more difficult to agree on collective climate action,

52
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:10,000
 but it also increasingly threatens to disrupt the flow of clean technology that is necessary to lower the cost and accelerate the speed of the green transition globally.

53
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:31,000
 With China now becoming the dominant supplier of solar panels, battery cells and electric vehicles, we are seeing an increasing trade-off between faster decarbonisation and greater economic security as countries seek to reduce their dependencies.

54
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:39,000
 Follow those developments by the day at the moment, but let's try to anticipate what the outcome will be.

55
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:44,000
 In turn, unmitigated climate change could strengthen fragmentary forces.

56
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:59,000
 For instance, an uneven distribution of extreme weather events may induce disorderly migration flows, straining international relations and encouraging policy makers to establish more barriers and promote more populism.

57
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:11,000
 One recent paper estimates that a changing climate could impel between 45 and 95 million working-age people to migrate over a short period of time.

58
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:27,000
 The third factor is that both risks are characterized by potential tipping points, that is, non-linearities, beyond which it could be very difficult to turn back.

59
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:37,000
 In the multilateral order, if it was to break down, history suggests that the opportunity to rebuild it again may be a long time coming.

60
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:53,000
 And indeed, every major overhaul of the international order, be it at the Congress of Vienna in the 19th century or the Bretton Woods Conference in the 20th, which I'm sure you will hear a lot about tomorrow because of Mr. Toussaint being with us,

61
00:08:53,000 --> 00:09:01,000
 was typically preceded and enabled by a major war.

62
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:07,000
 And if global heating were to reach a certain level, we may see irreversible transformations.

63
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:18,000
 For example, as warmer weather causes permafrost in polar regions to fall, stored methane is released into the atmosphere.

64
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:26,000
 This causes further heating and a self-reinforcing feedback loop emerge that is hardly irresistible.

65
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:35,000
 So what can we do to make our policies robust in such an environment?

66
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:40,000
 Well, let's think of the best case scenario.

67
00:09:40,000 --> 00:09:52,000
 That would be for countries to carve out areas that would be spared from geopolitical rivalry, such as working together towards net zero.

68
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:59,000
 And to find ways to increase mutual economic security without necessarily fragmenting world trade.

69
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:02,000
 Do you all believe in that?

70
00:10:02,000 --> 00:10:04,000
 Maybe not.

71
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:14,000
 So if we are more realistic, we must admit that with each passing day, this best case scenario looks less likely.

72
00:10:15,000 --> 00:10:28,000
 The World Bank, informed by the WTO, finds that almost 3000 trade restrictions were imposed last year alone, which is five times the amount in 2015.

73
00:10:28,000 --> 00:10:42,000
 So policymakers need to be prepared for a second best scenario in which these risks do start to reinforce each other and tipping points get closer.

74
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:49,000
 And this scenario is likely to create two tensions for central banks that we need to address.

75
00:10:49,000 --> 00:10:56,000
 The first tension is between what we can observe and what we can project.

76
00:10:56,000 --> 00:11:04,000
 The last few years have shown that making policy based on projections alone is likely to be misleading.

77
00:11:05,000 --> 00:11:13,000
 For instance, there were certain periods when recent inflation was the most informative signal about future inflation.

78
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:23,000
 And so the best policy was to overweight recent data relative to a necessarily uncertain forecast.

79
00:11:24,000 --> 00:11:33,000
 But as major shocks passed, we wish, we saw forecasts becoming much more accurate.

80
00:11:33,000 --> 00:11:45,000
 In 2023, for example, we saw a reduction of about 70% in the average absolute error in our staff projections relative to 2022.

81
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:47,000
 One quarter ahead.

82
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:58,000
 Relying too much on current data in this setting would have been equally misguided and would have led to policy falling behind the curve.

83
00:11:58,000 --> 00:12:13,000
 So the challenge for policymakers is that it is not always easy to know in real time which regime you are in, especially when you are around turning points.

84
00:12:14,000 --> 00:12:20,000
 And we cannot be changing our mind from one day to the next on what kinds of data are most important to us.

85
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:30,000
 For inflation expectations to remain anchored in an environment of structural changes and less quantifiable shocks,

86
00:12:30,000 --> 00:12:39,000
 people need to be able to broadly predict our reaction function and know what developments we will tolerate and which one we will not tolerate.

87
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:53,000
 And that is why I have argued that in the future, we will need to have ex-ante policy frameworks that combine both forward-looking and current-looking elements.

88
00:12:53,000 --> 00:13:07,000
 We need forecasts of the medium term, but we also need to be alert to the fact that available models have been educated using data from previous structural regimes that may no longer be valid.

89
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:19,000
 So analyzing current data and identifying persistent components allows us to account for structural changes and forecast the future in a more robust way.

90
00:13:20,000 --> 00:13:26,000
 And this is essentially the approach that we at the ECB have been adopting.

91
00:13:26,000 --> 00:13:38,000
 And I want to recognize and thank Philip Lane, sitting at our table and working hard with me on those issues and bringing all his intellect to those issues.

92
00:13:39,000 --> 00:13:41,000
 So since March, this is what we've been doing.

93
00:13:41,000 --> 00:13:51,000
 We deployed a three-sided reaction function to make our decision most robust, a forward-looking component, that is our inflation projections,

94
00:13:51,000 --> 00:14:06,000
 and two more current-looking ones, the dynamics of underlying inflation, of which we have multiple ways of measuring it and stripping it from less solid elements.

95
00:14:07,000 --> 00:14:11,000
 And third, the strength of our monetary policy transmission.

96
00:14:11,000 --> 00:14:21,000
 We have also made more use of scenario analysis to help us understand the risks around our projections if certain assumptions turn out differently.

97
00:14:22,000 --> 00:14:34,000
 And this framework served us well in calibrating when to stop raising rates, how long to hold them constant, and most recently when to start cutting them.

98
00:14:34,000 --> 00:14:43,000
 And for the time being, we will continue to use it to set the rate path in this uncertain environment.

99
00:14:44,000 --> 00:14:51,000
 That was the first tension. The second tension is between independence and interdependence.

100
00:14:51,000 --> 00:14:56,000
 I promise not to be too long because I could be very long on that one.

101
00:14:56,000 --> 00:15:02,000
 It is well known that central banks make decisions independently.

102
00:15:03,000 --> 00:15:09,000
 But those decisions are interdependent with the actions of other authorities.

103
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:18,000
 When policies are well aligned, that interdependence can lead to virtuous circles which help all authorities deliver their objectives.

104
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:30,000
 For example, increasing government investment to reduce energy supply constraints may lower medium-term inflation and make it less volatile.

105
00:15:30,000 --> 00:15:37,000
 That would in turn warrant lower policy rates over time, encouraging more investment and so on.

106
00:15:38,000 --> 00:15:50,000
 But faced with existential risks like geopolitical conflict and climate change, it is natural for people to ask whether central banks can actually contribute more explicitly.

107
00:15:50,000 --> 00:15:54,000
 And in my view, the answer to that question has two parts.

108
00:15:54,000 --> 00:16:04,000
 First, the evidence we have so far suggests that the new types of shocks we are facing are likely to put upward pressures on prices, at least initially.

109
00:16:05,000 --> 00:16:17,000
 One recent study based on data since 1900 finds that geopolitical risks lead to high inflation, lower economic activity and a fall in international trade.

110
00:16:17,000 --> 00:16:22,000
 And climate change is likely to initially appear as a negative supply shock.

111
00:16:22,000 --> 00:16:29,000
 Although over time, investment in renewable, greeds and storage will lead to lower and more stable energy prices.

112
00:16:30,000 --> 00:16:41,000
 So in this setting, I do not believe the ECB would be contributing to the European cause if we lost our focus on inflation and let inflation expectations drift upwards.

113
00:16:41,000 --> 00:16:54,000
 On the contrary, we know that the public detests high inflation and allowing it to become embedded in the economy would disrupt our politics and undermine all other geopolitical and climate goals.

114
00:16:55,000 --> 00:17:07,000
 However, and this is my second point, as a change in climate and geopolitical fragmentation have implications for the ECB mandate, there is scope for action within our mandate.

115
00:17:08,000 --> 00:17:12,000
 Let me give you three examples and then I conclude.

116
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:23,000
 The ECB now measures and monitors climate related risks and we have incorporated climate change considerations into our collateral framework.

117
00:17:23,000 --> 00:17:37,000
 Second example, currency swap lines are vital instruments in helping to reduce volatility, but they too have a geopolitical impact as they can strengthen the dynamics of major international currencies.

118
00:17:37,000 --> 00:17:58,000
 Third example, given the dominance of non-European digital payment firms, the launch of a digital euro would protect the strategic autonomy of European payments and monetary sovereignty, providing a fallback solution if geopolitical tensions were to intensify and exacerbate.

119
00:17:59,000 --> 00:18:12,000
 So, policy makers today are grappling with these new kinds of risks and we are not spared any new risks as the days go by.

120
00:18:12,000 --> 00:18:23,000
 While the best case scenario would be for policy makers to work together to prevent these risks from materializing, we have to be prepared for the second best world.

121
00:18:24,000 --> 00:18:36,000
 That could be a world marked by higher levels of uncertainty and volatility and it will create tensions for central banks that will have to resolve them.

122
00:18:36,000 --> 00:18:46,000
 But at the same time, my dear Boris, I'm reminded of the words of the Croatian poet Anton Branko Simic.

123
00:18:47,000 --> 00:18:56,000
 Man, be careful not to walk small under the star.

124
00:18:56,000 --> 00:18:58,000
 I'm not going to talk about our star.

125
00:18:58,000 --> 00:19:05,000
 But we cannot afford to walk small under the stars.

126
00:19:05,000 --> 00:19:08,000
 And certainly this is not what we will do tonight.

127
00:19:08,000 --> 00:19:15,000
 Because as Boris said, if you give your speech between the first course and the second course, then we can drink.

128
00:19:15,000 --> 00:19:19,000
 So, to Croatia and to the success of your conference.

129
00:19:19,000 --> 00:19:20,000
 Thank you very much.

130
00:19:21,000 --> 00:19:22,000
 Thank you very much.

131
00:19:22,000 --> 00:19:23,000
 Thank you very much.

